// ZeRO optimizer-state sharding correctness. Adam's m/v state is the biggest
// memory cost in large-model training; ZeRO shards it across N GPUs so each
// holds only 1/N. Because each element's update depends only on its own
// state, sharded AdamW must equal full AdamW bit-for-bit -- verified over 20
// steps for shard counts 2,4,5,8. This is the memory-scaling foundation that
// makes training a model too big for one GPU possible.
// EXPECT: ZERO: 4/4 PASS
fn app() { zero_adamw_selftest(); return 0.0; }
